Advanced Machine Learning - EasyVisa

Context

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired the firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist at EasyVisa have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

Facilitate the process of visa approvals. Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description

The data contains the different attributes of the employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

case_id: ID of each visa application

continent: Information of continent the employee

education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee

has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No

requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No

no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company

yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established

region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.

prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.

unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.

full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full-Time Position; N = Part-Time Position

case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

def plot_cat(df, column, rotation=45, figsize=(12,5), palette="tab10"):
    """
    Plots a Seaborn countplot and a Matplotlib pie chart for any categorical column.
    - Percentages are shown only in the legend (no overlapping).
    - Only xticks rotation is customizable.
    """
    counts = df[column].value_counts()
    labels = counts.index
    sizes = counts.values
    pcts = sizes / sizes.sum() * 100
    colors = sns.color_palette(palette, len(labels))

    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)

    # ---- Countplot ----
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sns.countplot(data=df, x=column, palette=palette)
    plt.title(f"{column} (Countplot)")
    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation)   # only option you asked to customize

    # ---- Pie Chart ----
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    wedges = plt.pie(
        sizes,
        colors=colors,
        startangle=90,
        textprops={'fontsize': 0}   # no labels inside  avoids overlap
    )[0]
    plt.title(f"{column} (Pie Chart)")
    plt.axis('equal')

    # Legend outside with percentages
    legend_labels = [f"{lab}  {pct:.1f}%" for lab, pct in zip(labels, pcts)]
    plt.legend(
        wedges,
        legend_labels,
        title="Categories",
        loc="center left",
        bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 0.5)
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def plot_num_distribution(df, column, bins = 30, figsize=(12,4)):
    """
    Plots Histogram with KDE and Boxplot for any numerical column.
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)

    # Histogram
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sns.histplot(df[column], kde=True, bins = bins, color="skyblue")
    plt.title(f"Histogram of {column}")

    # Boxplot
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    sns.boxplot(x=df[column], color="lightgreen")
    plt.title(f"Boxplot of {column}")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def stacked_barplot(df, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = df[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = df[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(df[predictor], df[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], df[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left",
        frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

Model Building - Original Data

Recall test score is important for Business problem.

Because in this problem, the cost of missing a Certified case is high.

A false negative means:

The model predicts Denied

But the actual case is Certified

  • A qualified applicant gets wrongly filtered out

  • Business loses a valid worker

  • OFLC process becomes inefficient

This is more harmful than a false positive.

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

Writing the user define function for model prediction and confusion matrix score.

In[58]:
model_names = []
accuracy_scores = []
precision_scores = []
recall_scores = []
f1_scores = []

def train_and_evaluate_model(model):
    # Fit model
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Predictions
    y_pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    y_pred_test = model.predict(X_test)

    # Train scores
    train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    train_precision = precision_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    train_recall = recall_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    train_f1 = f1_score(y_train, y_pred_train)

    # Test scores
    test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    test_precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    test_recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    test_f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred_test)

    # Print Train Results
    print("\n================ TRAINING PERFORMANCE ================")
    print(classification_report(y_train, y_pred_train))
    print("Train Accuracy:", train_acc)
    print("Train Precision:", train_precision)
    print("Train Recall:", train_recall)
    print("Train F1 Score:", train_f1)

    # Print Test Results
    print("\n================ TEST PERFORMANCE ================")
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_test))
    print("Test Accuracy:", test_acc)
    print("Test Precision:", test_precision)
    print("Test Recall:", test_recall)
    print("Test F1 Score:", test_f1)

    # Confusion Matrix (Train)
    print("\nConfusion Matrix - TRAIN DATA")
    ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_train, y_pred_train)
    plt.show()

    # Confusion Matrix (Test)
    print("\nConfusion Matrix - TEST DATA")
    ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_test, y_pred_test)
    plt.show()

    # Store test scores
    model_names.append(model)
    accuracy_scores.append(test_acc)
    precision_scores.append(test_precision)
    recall_scores.append(test_recall)
    f1_scores.append(test_f1)

model_names = []
accuracy_scores = []
precision_scores = []
recall_scores = []
f1_scores = []

def Undersampled_train_and_evaluate_model(model):
    # Fit model
    model.fit(X_train_under, y_train_under)

    # Predictions
    y_pred_train = model.predict(X_train_under)
    y_pred_test = model.predict(X_test)

    # Train scores
    train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train_under, y_pred_train)
    train_precision = precision_score(y_train_under, y_pred_train)
    train_recall = recall_score(y_train_under, y_pred_train)
    train_f1 = f1_score(y_train_under, y_pred_train)

    # Test scores
    test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    test_precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    test_recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    test_f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred_test)

    # Print Train Results
    print("\n================ TRAINING PERFORMANCE ================")
    print(classification_report(y_train_under, y_pred_train))
    print("Train Accuracy:", train_acc)
    print("Train Precision:", train_precision)
    print("Train Recall:", train_recall)
    print("Train F1 Score:", train_f1)

    # Print Test Results
    print("\n================ TEST PERFORMANCE ================")
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_test))
    print("Test Accuracy:", test_acc)
    print("Test Precision:", test_precision)
    print("Test Recall:", test_recall)
    print("Test F1 Score:", test_f1)

    # Confusion Matrix (Train)
    print("\nConfusion Matrix - TRAIN DATA")
    ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_train_under, y_pred_train)
    plt.show()

    # Confusion Matrix (Test)
    print("\nConfusion Matrix - TEST DATA")
    ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_test, y_pred_test)
    plt.show()

    # Store test scores
    model_names.append(model)
    accuracy_scores.append(test_acc)
    precision_scores.append(test_precision)
    recall_scores.append(test_recall)
    f1_scores.append(test_f1)

Hyperparameter Tuning and Model Performances

Following are 3 best performing models among all the models built previously with reason.

AdaBoost, Gradient Boosting and XGBoost with over sampling technique has strong reason for Hyperparameter Tuning. Using over sampled data for hyperparameter tuning to avoid imbalance. All 3 model has been chosen because of Recall is our priority. Following are reason for picking these 3 models.

1 AdaBoost (oversampled) Best recall (0.72 test)

  • Good test recall - it finds the most Certified cases.

  • Train vs test recall gap is small enough to be workable.

  • Best single-model starting point for maximizing recall.

GradientBoosting (over sampled) 2nd best recall (0.74 test)

  • Very high recall with good stability.

  • Good backup if AdaBoost overfits after heavy tuning.

XGBoost (oversampled) strong, robust (0.80 test)

  • High recall than AdaBoost/GB, but generally more stable and easier to regularize (fewest false negatives).

  • Good candidates if need robustness and feature-importance interpretability.

Using RandomizedSearchCV for Hyperparameter Tuning

In[92]:
RND = 42
cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=RND)
recall_scorer = make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label=1)

# ---------- AdaBoost ----------
ada = AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=RND)
ada_param_dist = {
        "estimator": [
        DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=d, min_samples_leaf=l, random_state=RND)
        for d in [1,2,3] for l in [1,2,4]
    ],
    "n_estimators": randint(50, 400),
    "learning_rate": uniform(0.01, 1.0)
}

# ---------- GradientBoosting (sklearn) ----------
gb = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=RND)
gb_param_dist = {
    "n_estimators": randint(100, 600),
    "learning_rate": uniform(0.01, 0.5),
    "max_depth": randint(2, 6),
    "min_samples_leaf": randint(1, 10),
    "subsample": uniform(0.6, 0.4)
}

# ---------- XGBoost ----------
xgb = XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False, eval_metric='logloss', random_state=RND)
xgb_param_dist = {
    "n_estimators": randint(100, 800),
    "learning_rate": uniform(0.01, 0.5),
    "max_depth": randint(3, 8),
    "subsample": uniform(0.6, 0.4),
    "colsample_bytree": uniform(0.5, 0.5),
    "gamma": uniform(0, 5),
    # optional imbalance handling
    "scale_pos_weight": [1, float(len(y_train_sm) - sum(y_train)) / (sum(y_train_sm) + 1e-6)]
}

# helper to run RandomizedSearchCV
def run_random_search(estimator, param_dist, n_iter=40, model_name="model"):
    rs = RandomizedSearchCV(
        estimator=estimator,
        param_distributions=param_dist,
        n_iter=n_iter,
        scoring=recall_scorer,
        cv=cv,
        verbose=1,
        n_jobs=-1,
        random_state=RND,
        return_train_score=False
    )
    t0 = time.time()
    rs.fit(X_train_sm, y_train_sm)
    t1 = time.time()
    print(f"\n{model_name} RandomizedSearchCV done in {(t1-t0):.1f}s  best CV recall={rs.best_score_:.4f}")
    print("best_params:", rs.best_params_)
    return rs

# Runing searches (choosing n_iter per model; smaller for AdaBoost because of many base_estimators)
rs_ada = run_random_search(ada, ada_param_dist, n_iter=30, model_name="AdaBoost")
rs_gb  = run_random_search(gb,  gb_param_dist,  n_iter=60, model_name="GradientBoosting")
rs_xgb = run_random_search(xgb, xgb_param_dist, n_iter=60, model_name="XGBoost")

Actionable Insights & Recommendations.

1. Business Problem Understanding.

The primary goal of the model is to correctly identify positive cases (Class 1). Therefore, Recall is the most important metric because:

  • Missing a true positive can result in loss of opportunity, regulatory impact, or operational inefficiency, depending on the dataset context.

  • High Recall ensures that most eligible/valid cases are flagged correctly.

2. Insights from Model Experiments. a. Base Models Summary.

  • Decision Tree overfits heavily and performs poorly on Recall Not suitable.

  • Random Forest improves Recall but still overfits; moderate generalization.

  • Bagging is stable but Recall is lower than boosting methods.

  • Gradient Boosting & AdaBoost show strong Recall but struggle with class imbalance.

  • XGBoost consistently delivers high Recall, better F1-score, and stable generalization.

Conclusion: Boosting algorithms outperform bagging and decision-tree-based models, especially under imbalanced conditions.

b. Impact of Oversampling vs Undersampling. Oversampling (SMOTE)

  • Significantly increases Recall for all models.

  • Prevents loss of important data (unlike undersampling).

  • Models generalize better and maintain balanced precision.

Undersampling

  • Causes information loss reduces model quality.

  • Lower recall for most algorithms.

  • Not preferred for this dataset.

Conclusion: Oversampling is the recommended approach, especially when recall is the priority.

c. Hyperparameter Tuning Results.

You tuned AdaBoost, GradientBoosting, and XGBoost.

AdaBoost (Tuned)

  • Recall improved but overall model remains weaker.

  • Struggles with Class 0 predictions and consistency.

  • Not the best candidate for final deployment.

GradientBoosting (Tuned)

  • Strong Recall (~0.81)

  • Good balance between precision and recall.

  • Stable model but slightly weaker than XGBoost.

XGBoost (Tuned)

  • Highest Recall (~0.825) among all tuned models.

  • Strong F1-score good balance of errors.

  • Generalizes well (train test performance).

  • Handles oversampled data most effectively.

Conclusion: XGBoost is the strongest model across all metrics, especially recall.

3. Final Model Recommendation Choose the Tuned XGBoost Model with Oversampled Training Data.

It provides:

  • Highest Recall - lowest false negatives

  • Best F1-score - balanced predictions

  • Good generalization without overfitting

  • Consistent performance across train & test

This makes XGBoost the most reliable, scalable, and production-friendly model.

Business Takeaways.

1. Higher Recall = Lower Operational Risk

  • The selected model ensures most positive cases are correctly detected, reducing business losses due to missed detections.

2. Improved Decision Quality

  • XGBoost maintains a strong balance between catching true positives and limiting false alarms.

  • Helps teams make faster and more accurate decisions.

3. Oversampling Strategy Increases Business Value

  • Enables the model to learn the minority class better.

  • Ensures fairness and consistency in predictions.
